    public void vacuumFloor() {
        System.out.println("Vacuuming floor...");
    }
}

public class VacuumCleaner implements Machine {
    // Implement the methods from the Machine interface
    public void washDishes() {
        System.out.println("Washing dishes...");
    }

    public void vacuumFloor() {
        System.out.println("Vacuuming floor...");
    }
}
```
In this example, `Machine` is an interface that defines the methods that all machines should have. The `Dishwasher` and `VacuumCleaner` classes implement this interface and provide their own implementation of these methods. 

You can create as many different types of machines or devices as you like by creating new classes that implement the `Machine` interface. Each class can have its own unique behaviors and properties, allowing for a wide variety of functionality to be encapsulated within each object.

